  'focusScopeDesc' => 
  array (
    'pl_PL' => '<p>Rocznik Administracji Publicznej jest recenzowanym interdyscyplinarnym czasopismem naukowym tworzonym przez pracowników Instytutu Politologii Uniwersytetu Pedagogicznego w Krakowie. Dzięki współpracy Instytutu z innymi ośrodkami naukowymi krajowymi i zagranicznymi (m.in. Uniwersytetem Jagiellońskim, Uniwersytetem Ekonomicznym w Krakowie, Uniwersytetem w Rzeszowie, Uniwersytetem w Radomiu oraz Uniwersytetem w Koszycach, Uniwersytetem w Essex i Uniwersytetem w Kijowie) Rocznik ma charakter międzyśrodowiskowy. Czasopismo jest wydawane w formie drukowanej oraz udostępniane na stronie internetowej w programie Open Journal Systems (wersja elektroniczna ma charakter referencyjny). Publikowane są w nim artykuły naukowe, recenzje, glosy i sprawozdania w języku polskim i angielskim. Rocznik Administracji Publicznej obejmuje następujące działy:</p><ul><li>administracyjne prawo materialne,</li><li>administracyjne prawo procesowe,</li><li>administracyjne prawo ustrojowe,</li><li>prawo i administrację Unii Europejskiej,</li><li>naukę o administracji,</li><li>historię administracji,</li><li>polityki publiczne,</li><li>zarządzanie w administracji publicznej.</li></ul><p>Czasopismo jest przeznaczone dla specjalistów z zakresu nauk o administracji i polityk publicznych, prawników zajmujących się prawem administracyjnym oraz prawem Unii Europejskiej, w tym sędziów, prokuratorów, urzędników państwowych, adwokatów i radców prawnych. Odbiorcami Rocznika są również pracownicy naukowi i studenci: prawa, administracji, politologii, stosunków międzynarodowych i bezpieczeństwa wewnętrznego.</p>',
    'en_US' => '<p>Public Administration Yearbook is a reviewed interdisciplinary scientific periodical founded by staff members from the Institute of Political Science at the Pedagogical University of Krakow. Thanks to the Institute\'s cooperation with other scientific centres home and abroad (e.g. the Jagiellonian University, Cracow University of Economics, the University of Rzeszow, the University of Technology and Humanities in Radom, the <span>Pavol Jozef Šafárik University in Košice</span>, the University of Essex and the University of Kyiv), the Yearbook involves a number of academic communities. The periodical is published in paper format and available online to make sure it reaches a wide audience. The features published in the periodical include scientific articles, reviews, glosses and reports in Polish and English. Public Administration Yearbook covers the following sections:</p><ul><li> Administrative material law,</li><li>Administrative procedural law,</li><li>Law of the administrative system,</li><li>Law and administration of the European Union,</li><li>Administrative science,</li><li>History of administration,</li><li>Public policies,</li><li>Management in public administration.</li></ul><p>The target readership includes specialists in administration sciences and public policies and lawyers practising administrative and EU law, including judges, prosecutors, public officials, barristers, solicitors, and legal counsels. The Yearbook is also read by academic teachers and students of: Law, Administration, Political Sciences, International Relations, and Public Security.</p><p> </p>',
  ),
  'about' => 
  array (
    'en_US' => '
							<div id="focusAndScope">
							<h3>Focus and Scope</h3>
							<p><p>Public Administration Yearbook is a reviewed interdisciplinary scientific periodical founded by staff members from the Institute of Political Science at the Pedagogical University of Krakow. Thanks to the Institute\'s cooperation with other scientific centres home and abroad (e.g. the Jagiellonian University, Cracow University of Economics, the University of Rzeszow, the University of Technology and Humanities in Radom, the <span>Pavol Jozef Šafárik University in Košice</span>, the University of Essex and the University of Kyiv), the Yearbook involves a number of academic communities. The periodical is published in paper format and available online to make sure it reaches a wide audience. The features published in the periodical include scientific articles, reviews, glosses and reports in Polish and English. Public Administration Yearbook covers the following sections:</p><ul><li> Administrative material law,</li><li>Administrative procedural law,</li><li>Law of the administrative system,</li><li>Law and administration of the European Union,</li><li>Administrative science,</li><li>History of administration,</li><li>Public policies,</li><li>Management in public administration.</li></ul><p>The target readership includes specialists in administration sciences and public policies and lawyers practising administrative and EU law, including judges, prosecutors, public officials, barristers, solicitors, and legal counsels. The Yearbook is also read by academic teachers and students of: Law, Administration, Political Sciences, International Relations, and Public Security.</p><p> </p></p>
							</div>
							<div id="peerReviewProcess">
							<h3>Peer Review Process</h3>
							<p><p><strong>Principles concerning the review of scientific contributions to Public Administration Yearbook</strong></p><ol><li>Articles sent to the Yearbook Editors are subject to formal editorial assessment. The Author shall be notified of preliminary approval and the submission of the article for a review or of the rejection of their text.</li><li>Once the Author’s (Authors’) identification data have been removed, the text shall be sent for a review.</li><li>Two Reviewers shall be appointed to review each article.</li><li>Articles shall be reviewed following a model where the Author(s) and Reviewers do not know their respective identities (double-blind review process<em>)</em>.</li><li>The article review shall be completed with a clear statement on:<ul type="a"><li>releasing the text for publication in its current form </li><li>releasing the text for publication with minor revisions </li><li>releasing the text for publication with major revisions </li><li>rejecting the article.</li></ul></li> <li>The qualification of the contribution for the successive stages of the publishing process shall be conditional upon two positive reviews. In the case of disputes, another Reviewer shall be appointed.</li><li>The Reviewers shall provide the Editors with completed review forms, by email, surface mail or directly to the Yearbook Editorial Office.</li><li>The Reviews shall be delivered on a specific review form available in electronic format on the Public Administration Yearbook website.</li><li>Comments made by the Reviewers shall be transmitted to the Author of the article being reviewed. The Author shall be obliged to take into consideration the recommendations and improve the text accordingly within a prescribed time. </li><li>If the Reviewers have expressed no objections or if the Author has followed the subject-related and formal recommendations they were given, the Editors shall give their final approval to have the text published, after which the text shall be subject to linguistic and editorial verification.</li><li>The names of the Reviewers of individual articles shall not be disclosed; once a year, Public Administration Yearbook shall make public a list of its collaborating Reviewers.</li></ol><p>Review process takes place on the review form.</p><p> </p><p><strong>REVIEWERS</strong></p> <p><strong> </strong></p> <p><strong>Anna Citkowska-Kimla</strong> (Jagiellonian University)</p> <p><strong>Małgorzata Czuryk</strong> (National Defence University, Warsaw)</p> <p><strong>Andrzej Jaeschke </strong>(Pedagogical University of Cracow)</p> <p><strong>Saulius Lukas Kaleda </strong>(Court of Justice of the European Union - Luxembourg)</p> <p><strong>Robert Kłaczyński </strong>(Pedagogical University of Cracow)</p> <p><strong>Krystyna Kowalik-Bańczyk </strong>(Institute of Law Studies of the Polish Academy of Sciences, Warsaw)</p> <p><strong>Małgorzata Kożuch </strong>(Jagiellonian University)</p> <p><strong>Paweł</strong> <strong>Laidler </strong>(Jagiellonian University)</p> <p><strong>Adam Łazowski </strong>(University of Westminster - London, United Kingdom)</p> <p><strong>Mislav Mataija</strong> (University of Zagreb, Croatia)</p> <p><strong>Janina Pach </strong>(Pedagogical University of Cracow)</p> <p><strong>Sławomir Patyra </strong>(Maria Curie Skłodowska University in Lublin)</p> <p><strong>Stanisław Piątek </strong>(University of Warsaw)</p> <p><strong>Danuta Plecka</strong> (Nicolaus Copernicus University in Toruń)</p> <p><strong>André Saddy </strong>(Fluminense Federal University  - Rio de Janeiro, Brazil)</p> <p><strong>Piotr Tusiński </strong>(Pedagogical University of Cracow)</p></p>
							</div>
							<div id="openAccessPolicy">
							<h3>Open Access Policy</h3>
							<p><p>To be accepted by the editors of Public Administration Yearbook, texts to be printed must be original and not yet published elsewhere. The contents of the periodical are available under the Creative Commons (CC-BY-NC-ND 3.0 PL) license</p> <p><a href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0/legalcode" target="_blank"><img src="/~wwwaupc/public/site/images/wojt/cc-by-nc-nd3.png" alt="" width="150" height="52" /></a></p> <p>The license allows for the use of materials published in Public Administration Yearbook for non-commercial purposes, e.g. commentary, critique, information, archiving, teaching or research, in compliance with the copyright legislation in force (Act of 4 February 1994 on copyright and related rights, Journal of Laws 1994 no 24 item 83, as amended). The license requires that sources cited or paraphrased be referred to precisely and the text retain its original form (no derivative works may be created).</p> <p> </p></p>
							</div>',
